.\" Manpage for hsh
.\" Contact Anna Halaapiapi, Tran Nguyen, and Toni Mathieson to correct errors or typos.
.TH HSH 1 "22 August 2025" "Version 1.0" "Holberton Simple Shell Project - User Manual"


.SH NAME
hsh \- a simple shell interpretation of the standard shell


.SH SYNOPSIS
.B ./hsh command [option] [FILE]

Following execution, the shell will display the prompt "$ " where users can enter commands.


.SH DESCRIPTION
This project is a simple Unix shell implemented in the C programming language. It replicates a subset of standard shell behaviour, such as executing programs, handling environment variables and responding to user input.

This simple shell has both interactive and non-interactive modes, where commands can either be entered to the running shell, or through an executed file (see below).


.SH OPTIONS
hsh will enter the interactive mode of the simple shell.

Commands can be entered right into the command line. Command options will be entered after the main command.


.SH ENVIRONMENT VARIABLES
The following environment variables shall affect the execution of hsh:


PATH    Directories to search for commands
HOME    The home directory
PWD     The current working directory
OLDPWD  The previous working directory
USER    The name of the current user
SHELL   The absolute path to the user's default shell
TERM    The type of terminal being used


.SH BUILTINS
The following builtin commands are supported:

.B exit
- Exit the shell

.B env
- Prints environment variables from the current environment.

.B cd [Directory]
- Changes the current directory to the given directory.

.B clear
- Clears the terminal screen using an escape sequence


.SH RETURN VALUE
The return value will 0 if successful. Otherwise a non-zero number will be displayed.


.SH EXIT STATUS
The shell will exit with one of the following statuses:

0       Successful execution of the shell or command
1       Error with exit
127     Command not found or execve failed


.SH EXAMPLES

.B Example (Interactive mode):
.nf
$ ./hsh
($) /bin/ls
hsh main.c shell.c
($) exit
$
.fi
.br

.B Example (Non-interactive mode):
.br
.nf
$ echo "/bin/ls" | ./hsh
hsh main.c shell.c test_ls_2
$ cat test_ls_2
/bin/ls
/bin/ls
$ cat test_ls_2 | ./hsh
hsh main.c shell.c test_ls_2
hsh main.c shell.c test_ls_2
.fi


